The explicitly declared generated column is kept:
a	Nullable(Int64)					
b	Nullable(Int64)					
Insert without a column list, and an explicit base-column list, both target only the base column; SQLite computes the generated column:
a	b
1	2
2	3
The generated column is MATERIALIZED, so SELECT * returns only the base column:
a
1
2
Explicitly writing into the generated column is rejected:
Cannot insert column b, because it is MATERIALIZED column
The rejected insert wrote nothing:
a	b
1	2
2	3
SHOW CREATE TABLE round-trips the generated column as an ordinary column (no MATERIALIZED keyword):
`b` Nullable(Int64)
Recreating the table from that round-tripped definition keeps the generated column non-insertable:
Cannot insert column b, because it is MATERIALIZED column
